---
description: One React component per TSX file; helpers in sibling utils/helpers beside the feature or component folder
alwaysApply: true
---

One component per.tsx file

Exactly one React component per *.tsx file (one function/class/forwardRef component that is the file’s UI unit). Do not define additional components in the same file—not even small inner function Row() or const Badge = () => … helpers used only locally.
Split into another *.tsx file in the same feature (or into a component-named subfolder—see below) and compose via imports.
Files that export only hooks (no JSX) should use *.ts, not *.tsx.

Where utilities live

No general-purpose helpers inside the component *.tsx file. Move pure functions to:
src/features/<feature>/utils/… or helpers/… for feature-wide helpers, or
Next to the component under a folder named for that component, e.g. components/chat-session/chat-session.utils.ts, when the logic is specific to that screen/piece.
Name files predictably: *.utils.ts, *.helpers.ts, or something.utils.ts colocated with the one component that primarily uses them.

Suggested layout (component-specific)

src/features/chat/components/chat-session/
  chat-session.tsx           # only ChatSession
  chat-session.utils.ts      # formatters, guards, constants for ChatSession

Exceptions

Routes and framework files (page.tsx, layout.tsx, loading.tsx, etc.) may stay minimal; still prefer extracting UI into feature components that each follow this rule.
Tests (*.test.tsx) and story files may co-locate with the component without changing the production file rule.
